post_text:
Starting Monday, September 14th, in Madison, the 5th through 12th grade students will board a bus in front of MMN Elementary. If needed, students may wait under the front overhang.

The buses will drop off the elementary students around 7:50 and pull ahead to pick up the 5-12 students. Once a bus is near 50% capacity it will leave the for the 5-12 building.

At dismissal, the buses will arrive at MMN around 3:20. Family members of 5-12 bus students may arrive and depart MMN Elementary with their siblings.

post_text:
Earlier today, we were informed that a member of the LQPV/DB Cross Country team tested positive for COVID-19. With the guidance of the Minnesota Department of Health and Countryside Public Health all members of the cross-country team were sent home this afternoon. The students last contact with that student was at practice on Friday, September 4th. Students and coaches need to be quarantined for 14 days. Students that are not a member of the cross-country team do not need to quarantine at this time. Should that information change, families will be notified.

As always, LQPV’s goal is to ensure a safe learning environment for our students and staff. Please be assured that we are diligently following our COVID procedures.

post_text:
’Twas the night before the 2020 school year starts,📚📝📓
And this year has been crazy! 📆
E-learning or in person, 💻
No one can be lazy! 🤓
A lot to keep up with! 🥱
Details are a'plenty! 📑🗂
Any fever or cough? 🤒😪
(No, we don’t have any.) 🤷🏻‍♀️
The masks are all sitting by the doorway with care, 😷
All colors and styles, so, germies beware! 🦠 🧬
The chrome books are charging because in this district we use Google classroom,🖥
To teachers and staff, we thank you! 👩🏼‍🏫
And bless this year’s class. 🙏🏻
The nerves and confusion, 😔
We know they will pass. ✔️
The kiddos are ready, 👦🏼👦🏼👦🏼
In person and afar. 🧍🏼‍♂️🧍🏻‍♀️👨🏼‍💻
And remember, all children:
You are a bright star. 🌟 ❤️

#WeAreLQPV #LQPVbacktoschool2020

✨Poem credit Brooks Bjerke✨

post_text:
Late yesterday one of the staff members at Appleton-Milan Elementary School let her principal know that she had tested positive for COVID-19. The Minnesota Department of Health and Countryside Public Health are aware of the situation. Guidance sought from Countryside Public Health was as follows: “If her test comes back positive, she will need to ISOLATE for 10 days from the date the test was obtained.”

The individual has not entered any of the school buildings since before August 22 and will not be allowed to return to any of the buildings until Friday, September 4, 2020. Please be assured that the Lac qui Parle Valley Schools are following the guidelines issued by the CDC, the Minnesota Department of Health, and Countryside Public Health.

Thank you,
Greg Schmidt, Superintendent

shared_text:
Minnesota Department of Education
July 9 at 12:28 PM ·

Thank you to the more than 130,000 families who took the time to complete our Fall Planning Survey. We heard your stories of challenging times and the hardship that distance learning placed on you and your loved ones. We also heard your gratitude for keeping our communities safe and spending more time with families.
Your experiences are invaluable as we plan for the 2020-21 school year during these times of uncertainty. It is our shared goal to lift up our students through education, while keeping them safe. Your voices will undoubtedly help us do that.
You can find the full results of our Fall Planning Survey on our website here: https://education.mn.gov/MDE/dse/health/covid19/publicEng/.
As we look toward the future, please know Minnesota school districts and charter schools are working extremely hard to support our students, families and educators. With your help, we will find innovative solutions to the challenges of our times.

Planning ahead for possible emergencies is even more important during the COVID-19 pandemic. One key priority is knowing what to do if a parent or guardian becomes sick or hospitalized due to the virus.

The Minnesota Department of Health (MDH) has created a kit that parents can complete online and then share it with alternative caregivers, family, neighbors, teachers or child care providers: https://mn.gov/mmb-stat/childrens-cabinet/covid-19-emergency-family-planning.pdf.

More MDH resources on how to talk to children about emergency preparedness and COVID-19 can be found in the Family Resources section here: https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/ep/behavioral/covid19.html#family.

Prom Announcement:

Dawn Hegland (Prom Coordinator) and Scott Sawatzky have been in communication with Countryside Public Health and some junior students (along with a few parents) that are on the daybreak committee. With the current guidelines and recommendations for COVID-19, we have decided to cancel prom for the 2020 school year. The junior class plans to use some of their fundraised money to give prizes to all juniors and seniors of this year's class (we are still determining how to go about doing that). The remaining money they fundraised will be used in conjunction with next year's junior class to collaborate for the 2021 prom.

Minnesota is now offering funds for families of children ages 5 to 18 who qualify for free or reduced-price school meals. The new program, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT), will provide up to $325 per child that families can use to purchase nutritious food for their household. Approximately 350,000 Minnesota children could benefit.

Learn more at: www.mn.p-ebt.org

shared_text:
LQPV Community Education & Rec
June 10 at 11:57 AM ·

Summer Rec Update: 6/10/2020

Community Education will have limited summer rec classes beginning July 13th through August 5th.

Unfortunately, after sending out the newsletter last week in hope of sustaining most summer rec classes, that won’t be happening as planned.

There won’t be baseball, softball, or any other rec classes such as PE Games, etc.

We will hold Arts and crafts classes in Appleton and Madison on Monday’s and Wednesday’s beginning on July 13th. A total of three classes will be held on Mondays and Wednesday’s. Online Registration for these classes will begin next week. We ask that you sign up for one of the three time slots available. No walk ins please!

Also: Community Education will open up online registration for a school of fish class that will be held out at the high school on Tuesday, August 4th in July.

These are both interesting and sad times for us all! It can only get better! 😃

post_text:
Congrats to the YES! Team on their All Star State Championship Award!!!

On June 2nd, the 2020 Youth Eco Solutions (YES!) State Championship Award Ceremony took place via Zoom. YES! staff, coaches, students, and judges joined the meeting to celebrate and recognize teams for their outstanding work during the 2019-20 YES! season. The teams submitted final reports and were scored by a panel of judges in the following categories: Project Planning & Completion, Goal Setting & Team Work, Ecological Impact, Community Impact, and Water Stewardship.

Thank you to everyone who submitted a name suggestion during our elementary school naming contest! We had several submissions. We wanted to share a few of the top ideas with the community before our final survey (see photos below). As shown, the new name will be prefaced with ‘Lac qui Parle Valley’ and end with ‘Elementary’. (This will hold true even if the final survey result is to keep the current building names.) To help us narrow down the choices, please “like” the names you like best!

(Please note: The final survey will be put out in the coming days. The option to keep the existing names will be on the final survey.)

post_text: Seniors, today is your last day of high school. This picture was taken on the first day of school back in September. A lack of closure to properly close this chapter in your life. Though we did not get a proper "last day" photo, rest assured, we ARE in this together. We ARE trying our best to support you. post_text:
News Release April 20, 2020

Through the coordinated efforts of the Lac qui Parle County Sheriff’s Office, the Lac qui Parle County Attorney’s Office, the MN Bureau of Criminal Apprehension and staff members at the Lac qui Parle Valley Schools, the author of the threatening message written on the wall of a bathroom stall in late February was identified and has confessed to writing the message.
It was determined that the student acted alone and, given the individual's cooperation, the school district no longer considers the matter a threat to students or staff. The student has been removed from the school pending discipline. Since the author is a minor, we are unable to release information about the individual.
We appreciate everyone’s patience and assistance during this investigation.

Gregory A. Schmidt, LqPV School Superintendent

It was determined that the student acted alone and, given the individual's cooperation, the school district no longer considers the matter a threat to students or staff. The student has been removed from the school pending discipline. Since the author is a minor, we are unable to release information about the individual.

post_text:
Prom Update:

Due to the COVID-19 Pandemic, the Lac qui Parle Valley Prom, originally scheduled for May 2, is being postponed. The plan is to find two alternative dates. Option #1 would be a date in June and Option #2 would be a date in July. If the COVID-19 Pandemic pushes into the date that is selected for July, Lac qui Parle Valley would be forced to make the difficult decision to cancel prom for the 2020 school year.

One of the challenges we are facing is to find a site, as the Lac qui Parle Valley schools will be under construction during the summer months. The other concern that the prom/daybreak committee is working through is finding a date that works for the entertainment and vendors that have been reserved for the original May date. Lac qui Parle Valley will continue to inform our students, parents, and community members on the outcome of the 2020 prom festivities.
text:
Prom Update:

Due to the COVID-19 Pandemic, the Lac qui Parle Valley Prom, originally scheduled for May 2, is being postponed. The plan is to find two alternative dates. Option #1 would be a date in June and Option #2 would be a date in July. One of the challenges we are facing is to find a site, as the Lac qui Parle Valley schools will be under construction during the summer months. The other concern that the prom/daybreak committee is working through is finding a date that works for the entertainment and vendors that have been reserved for the original May date. Lac qui Parle Valley will continue to inform our students, parents, and community members on the outcome of the 2020 prom festivities.

post_text:
Tomorrow begins our first day of Distance Learning. Please remind students that these classroom rules still apply. Remember, we are all in this together and if you have questions please don't hesitate to reach out! #InThisTogether #DistanceLearningLQPV

Reminder of the Attendance Policy:
-Elementary students: Teachers will take attendance using class dojo/Bloomz or paper packet signatures. Your child's teacher will inform you of how they will be taking attendance.
-Middle/High School (5-12): Students will need to log into each of their classes using Google Classroom, every day that school is in session. Teachers will have a “Google Classroom Question” that will track students logging in. Students have until 11:59 PM each school day to log in.

If you are in need of technical support please send an email to draddatz@lqpv.org or call 320-752-4820.

Visit our website,www.lqpv.org/content/distance-learning, for more information.

Because of the need for social distancing, please wave from your window or yard. If you do not live on one of these streets, park along the street and wave from your car or from the curb. ☑️ Put household plan into action.

☑️ Individuals with underlying medical conditions should consider staying home and avoiding gatherings or other situations of potential exposures, including travel.

post_text:
Lac qui Parle Valley Schools takes the safety of our students and staff very seriously and is actively working with law enforcement to investigate a threatening message discovered after school at Lac qui Parle Valley High School on Wednesday, February 26. The Lac qui Parle Sheriff’s Office is leading the investigation of the incident.

Due to the timing of the discovery of the threat, the school elected to close as a precautionary measure to allow the initial investigation into the matter. The school district is enhancing their security to ensure the safety of students and staff. Those changes will take place immediately.

The Lac qui Parle Valley Schools will open on time on Monday, March 2.

If you have information related to this incident, please contact the Lac qui Parle Sheriff’s Department at 320-598-3720.

Allen Anderson, Sheriff - Lac qui Parle County
Greg Schmidt, Superintendent - Lac qui Parle Valley Schools
